I read, many years ago, (don't know whether it is true or not) that anti war people held a planning meeting.  The major question of the meeting was to decide whether to use passive or confrontational means to achieve their goals.  They chose confrontational means to achieve their goals.<br><br>
If their is a &quot;lesson&quot; to learn from the sixties and seventies and I repeat &quot;if,&quot; then hopefully it is that we can better present our ideas for change in a non confrontational manner.  I confess to be a &quot;little&quot; naive, but I believe, whenever possible, it is more productive to place priority on long term &quot;strageties&quot; to achieve success rather than short term &quot;sound or visual bites.&quot;  The goings on in our &quot;home&quot; here make my point.<br><br>
I know that I can be swayed to changed myself, or buy something with the soft sell.  Many salesman and businesses are learning this lesson well, althought slowly.<br><br>
I'm not sure who it was that said that we rarely if ever see the results of our good actions (on a national or global level) in our lifetime.  Another example of sad, but true.<br><br>
I am assuming that all of us, vets and non vets, hawks and resistors, know of someone who does not share our views that we respect and admire.  I believe it comes down to a matter of class, which is like, what a judge once said, is like pornography.  I know it when I see it, but I don't know how to describe it.<br><br>
Oops, one of my favorite words, I've run on again.  My best to all -- for tomorrow is Veterans Day.<br><br>
